item.title: 2's compliment
item.description:
To convert a denary negative number to binary, the positive version of the number must first be converted into binary.
Take for example: 37
This in binary is 00100101.
To convert this into a negative number, all the bits are "flipped", this means that if they are a 1, they become a 0 and if they are a 0, they become a 1. 1 is then added to the least significant bit.
00100101 11011011.
With 2's compliment, the left most bit (MSB) dictates the sign (this is the sign bit). Because in this instance the msb is a 1, we know that it must be a negative number.

item.title: acceleration
item.description:
Definition Acceleration can be considered the rate of change of velocity.

The SI unit of acceleration is .
When an object falls, its velocity changes and so its velocity increases. An alternative equation for acceleration is:Where is acceleration, is an objects final velocity, is the initial velocity and is the time.
If the final velocity is greater than the original velocity, then the object has sped up and accelerated, however if it is less than the original velocity, then it has decelerated.
The acceleration direction will be the direction of the resultant vector: acceleration has a direction and so it is considered a vector.
Uniform acceleration means that the acceleration is at a steady rate, and some equations can only be calculated if th acceleration are uniform. Some of these equations are the SUVAT equations.
Non-uniform acceleration is where the direction or speed of the motion changes, and so the acceleration changes. If the acceleration is non-uniform and the instantaneous acceleration is to be found, a tangent is drawn on the velocity-time graph, with its gradient calculated.

item.title: control bus
item.description:
Buses carry data and instructions around the CPU. There are 3 types of bus:

control bus


This bus carries control signals and is bidirectional. This means that signals can travel to and from every component on the CPU. Every component can send and receive signals on the control bus. This bus is responsible for carrying control signals: including but not limited to:

memory read: tells memory that a component wants to read it
memory write: tells memory that a component wants to write to it
bus request: requests the use of a bus
bus grant: grants the request of a bus
clock

data bus


This bus carries data between components, and is partly unidirectional, and partly bidirectional, in the sense that most components can send and receive signals on this bus, aside from input controllers which can only send signals, and output controllers, which can only receive signals.
The width of the data bus is how many wires or lines are attributed to the bus.
If the data bus width is the same as the word length of the system, data can be transferred to and from memory in a single tick. Otherwise, it will take more ticks, therefore bus width affects overall performance.

address bus


This bus sends memory addresses from the processor to CPU components. For this reason, the address bus is unidirectional, only allowing signals to be sent one way. It's width dictates the maximum possible word length and memory address of the CPU. For example, a 32 bit bus can reference addresses.
The width of the bus determines how much can be sent along it.

The gold leaf displays charge as the electrons flow through it and repel from the metal stem.

The zinc plate on top of the gold leaf electroscope is negatively charged from rubbing an insulator and holding it near the plate. The lost electrons from the insulator are transferred onto the zinc plate, making it negatively charged. This flows through the metal stem and onto the gold leaf, which causes it to repel from the metal stem.

The electrons can be knocked off the zinc plate using ultraviolet light. The photons from the UV light have a high enough frequency and therefore energy to knock off the electrons from the metal plate.
Before this experiment, scientists thought that light travelled in waves, and so light shone continuously at the plate should be able to discharge the plate eventually. This does not happen, meaning that the wave model for light cannot be applied.
Therefore, photons must transfer energy to the electrons (1 photon to 1 electron). They must also reach a threshold frequency in order to release the electrons from the surface, so the lower frequency visible light photons do not have enough energy to discharge the plate, but the ultraviolet photons do.

Optical fibres work by using total internal reflection to carry light along a transparent fibre. The light ray is totally internally reflected, unless a radius of a bend is too small. This is because at each point where the light ray reaches a boundary, the angle of incidence exceeds the critical angle.

Optical fibres are used in telecommunications because they are smaller, cheaper and more sustainable to transfer binary. Shorter distances use plastic as its cheaper, though long distances use glass as it doesnt absorb as much light energy as the plastic. Repairs are not as easy as with copper cables, as copper cables can be soldered together.

An endoscope is used to look into the human body so that surgery isnt required. It contains 2 bundles of fibre optic cables; one is used to shine light into the body, and the other is used to transmit the light back up to the outside.

There are 3 layers in an optical fibre, the core, the cladding and the outer sheath. the optically dense core is where the light shines through, the cladding prevents the light from shining out of the core and the sheath prevents the internal components from being scratched.


As a pulse travels down a fibre, the dispersion causes the pulse to spread. This limits the bit rate of data transfer. This is limited by making the core of the fibre more narrow. This prevents the path difference from becoming too big.

Because different wavelengths travel at different speeds, they arrive at different times. Therefore, light of the same colour or infrared light is passed down the core. Material dispersion also occurs when the core absorbs the light. To prevent this, a core that is extremely transparent is used, as well as repeaters that amplify the fading signal.

A medical endoscope contains two bundles; one for shining light and one for receiving light. Because it doesn't matter how the light is sent to the site, this bundle can be incoherent. This means that the fibres aren't arranged in any particular order. When the light returns out from the body, it does matter which way the fibres are arranged, because it needs to form an image to be interpreted.
Therefore, a coherent bundle is formed, so that the fibres are in the same relative position at both ends. This means that an image can be produced so doctors can see inside patients.

recordable formats use a transparent dye that becomes opaque when heated with a laser.
re-writable formats use a laser to change the state of a phase-change alloy and a magnet to set a new state.

item.title: UPC-A
item.description:
The UPC-A (as well as the EAN) barcodes are punctuated with long guard bars to show the start middle and end of the barcode. The left side is the manufacturer number, and the right is the product number.
Below the lines themselves there are numbers that correspond to what the barcode is representing. There is also a start digit and a check digit to calibrate the scanner.
Numbers are represented inversely on the left and right sides; what bars would be black on one side would be white on the other for the same digit. There will always be an odd number of black bars on the left hand side, meaning it is easy to determine what side a digit is from.
